The virus initially replicates in the epithelium of the upper respiratory tract, with subsequent spread within a few days to the lower tract airways (Fig. 68-1
). Early inflammation of the bronchial and bronchiolar epithelium occurs along with peribronchiolar infiltration, mostly with mononuclear cells, and edema of the submucosa and adventitia. The respiratory epithelium becomes necrotic and is sloughed into the lumina of the airways. Subsequently, the epithelium proliferates and shows cuboidal cells without cilia (Fig. 68-2
).
